# Assignment 2 Advanced API Configuration Update

I, Demetre, enhanced my existing Spring Boot REST API project. I did not create a new project. I added externalized configuration with profiles, validated custom application settings, REST internationalization, localized validation errors, structured logging, and rolling file logs.

## Conceptual Update Log

- I separated common configuration from environment-specific configuration.
- I added the `dev` profile for local development with an in-memory H2 database and seeded test users.
- I added the `prod` profile for production-style execution with PostgreSQL settings driven by environment variables.
- I created a validated custom configuration POJO using `@ConfigurationProperties(prefix = "app.settings")`.
- I injected those custom settings into a metadata controller so `/api/meta` returns dynamic API metadata.
- I configured REST locale resolution through the `Accept-Language` request header.
- I added UTF-8 message bundles with default Georgian messages and English messages.
- I localized validation messages by using message bundle keys in DTO validation annotations.
- I added a global REST exception handler that returns structured localized JSON error responses.
- I replaced informal output practices with SLF4J logging patterns.
- I added meaningful logs in authentication, user management, wardrobe piece management, file storage, and exception handling.
- I configured logs to write to `logs/app.log` with rolling log files.
- I configured dev logging to be more verbose and prod logging to be stricter.

## Custom Configuration Properties

The custom class is `AppSettingsProperties` and uses the prefix:

```text
app.settings
```

Fields:

```text
app.settings.title
app.settings.default-page-limit
app.settings.support-email
app.settings.external-style-service-url
app.settings.ai-suggestions-enabled
```

The fields are validated with annotations such as `@NotBlank`, `@Min`, `@Max`, and `@Email`.

## Profiles

Run with the development profile:

```powershell
mvn spring-boot:run -Dspring-boot.run.profiles=dev
```

Run with the production profile:

```powershell
mvn spring-boot:run -Dspring-boot.run.profiles=prod
```

In an IDE, set the active Spring profile to either:

```text
dev
prod
```

The default profile is `dev`.

## Internationalization

The API reads the requested language from the standard `Accept-Language` HTTP header.

Test English:

```powershell
curl -H "Accept-Language: en" http://localhost:8080/api/meta
```

Test Georgian/default messages:

```powershell
curl -H "Accept-Language: ka" http://localhost:8080/api/meta
```

Validation errors are also localized. For example, sending an invalid registration request to `POST /api/auth/register` returns localized field errors.

## Structured Logging

Logs are printed to the console and written to:

```text
backend/logs/app.log
```

Rolling log files use this pattern:

```text
backend/logs/app-yyyy-MM-dd.N.log
```

The dev profile uses more detailed logging for `com.wardrobe`, while the prod profile uses stricter root logging.
